-> Why Sealed Classes Came into Java?

    -> Normally, inheritance is mainly used for:
        -> Code Reuse
        -> Extending existing functionality

    -> Example:
        -> Suppose class Shape already contains:
            -> common fields
            -> common methods
        -> Then Circle and Square can reuse that code by extending Shape

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Problem Before Sealed Classes:

        -> Any class from anywhere could extend Shape

        -> Example:

                class Triangle extends Shape { }
                class Hexagon extends Shape { }
                class RandomShape extends Shape { }

        -> Library owner loses control over hierarchy

        -> This becomes dangerous when:
            -> You want to model FIXED domain possibilities
            -> You want strict control over inheritance
            -> You want only specific subclasses

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Real World Thinking:

        -> Imagine graphics library creator says:

            -> "In my library, only these shapes are valid:"
                -> Circle
                -> Square
                -> Rectangle

            -> I do NOT want users creating:
                -> WeirdShape
                -> UnknownShape
                -> CustomShape

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Solution = Sealed Class

        -> Sealed class allows parent class to control:
            -> Who can extend it

        -> Parent class explicitly declares permitted subclasses

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Example:

            public sealed class Shape
                permits Circle, Square, Rectangle {

            }

            final class Circle extends Shape { }

            final class Square extends Shape { }

            final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Meaning:

        -> Only:
            -> Circle
            -> Square
            -> Rectangle

           can extend Shape

        -> Any other class trying to extend Shape gives compile-time error

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Main Goal of Sealed Classes:

        -> Restrict inheritance
        -> Model fixed set of possibilities
        -> Improve domain modeling
        -> Improve security/control
        -> Help compiler understand hierarchy better

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Very Important Point:

        -> Sealed class is opposite of open inheritance

        -> Normal inheritance:
            -> "Anyone can extend me"

        -> Sealed inheritance:
            -> "Only selected classes can extend me"

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Best Use Cases:

        -> Domain models
        -> State machines
        -> AST trees
        -> Geometry libraries
        -> Payment types
        -> Vehicle hierarchy
        -> Expression trees

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Example:

            sealed interface Payment
                permits CreditCard, UPI, Cash { }

            final class CreditCard implements Payment { }

            final class UPI implements Payment { }

            final class Cash implements Payment { }

        -> Now payment types are fixed and controlled

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Simple Memory Trick:

        -> "sealed" means:
            -> Closed for unknown subclasses
            -> Open only for permitted subclasses

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Before Sealed Class:
    
            Shape
               ↑
        Anyone can extend

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> After Sealed Class:

                    Shape
                  /   |   \
             Circle Square Rectangle

        -> Only permitted classes allowed

=> Declaring Sealed Class:
    
    -> In different file: If you want to declare permitted subclasses in different files, you must use "permits" clause in the sealed class declaration.

        -> Syntax:

                public sealed class ClassName
                    permits Subclass1, Subclass2, ... {
                }

        -> Example:

                public sealed class Shape
                    permits Circle, Square, Rectangle {

                }

                public final class Circle extends Shape { }
                public final class Square extends Shape { }
                public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }
        
    -> In same file:
        -> you can define permitted subclass in the same file without using "permits" clause:

                public sealed class Shape {

                }

                final class Circle extends Shape { }

                final class Square extends Shape { }

                final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Constraints on Permitted Subclasses:
        
        -> They must be accessible by the sealed class at compile time.
            -> For Example:
                -> To compile Shape, compiler must be able to find Circle, Square, and Rectangle

        -> Permitted subclasses must be in the same module or package as the sealed class

        -> Permitted subclasses must be declared as below modifier to describe their relationship with the sealed class:
            -> final: Cannot be extended further
            -> sealed: Can be extended by other sealed or non-sealed classes
            -> non-sealed: Can be extended by any class

            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle {

                    }

                    // Circle is final, cannot be extended further
                    final class Circle extends Shape { }

                    // Square is sealed, can be extended by other sealed or non-sealed classes
                    sealed class Square extends Shape
                        permits ColoredSquare {

                    }

                    // Rectangle is non-sealed, can be extended by any class
                    non-sealed class Rectangle extends Shape { }

                    final class ColoredSquare extends Square { }

    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Declaring Sealed Interface:

        -> Similar to sealed class, you can declare a sealed interface with "sealed" keyword and "permits" clause.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed interface Payment
                        permits CreditCard, UPI, Cash { }

                    final class CreditCard implements Payment { }

                    final class UPI implements Payment { }

                    final class Cash implements Payment { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Record Classes as permitted subclasses:

        -> Record classes can also be permitted subclasses of a sealed class or interface.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed interface Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape { }

                    public record Square(double side) implements Shape { }

                    public record Rectangle(double width, double height) implements Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Pattern Matching:

        -> Sealed classes work well with pattern matching (introduced in Java 16) because the compiler knows all possible subclasses.

        -> This allows for exhaustive pattern matching, where the compiler can check if all cases are handled.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed interface Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape { }

                    public record Square(double side) implements Shape { }

                    public record Rectangle(double width, double height) implements Shape { }

                    public class ShapeAreaCalculator {
                        public double calculateArea(Shape shape) {
                            return switch (shape) {
                                case Circle c -> Math.PI * c.radius() * c.radius();
                                case Square s -> s.side() * s.side();
                                case Rectangle r -> r.width() * r.height();
                            };
                        }
                    }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Serialization:

        -> Sealed classes can be serialized, but all permitted subclasses must also be serializable.

        -> This ensures that the entire hierarchy can be serialized and deserialized correctly.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Shape implements Serializable
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public record Circle(double radius) extends Shape { }

                    public record Square(double side) extends Shape { }

                    public record Rectangle(double width, double height) extends Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Reflection:

        -> Reflection in java allows you to inspect classes and their members at runtime. With sealed classes, you can still use reflection to inspect the class and its permitted subclasses.

        -> Sealed classes can be inspected using reflection, but the permitted subclasses are also known at compile time.

        -> This allows for better performance and security when using reflection with sealed classes.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public record Circle(double radius) extends Shape { }

                    public record Square(double side) extends Shape { }

                    public record Rectangle(double width, double height) extends Shape { }

                    public class ReflectionExample {
                        public static void main(String[] args) {
                            Class<?> shapeClass = Shape.class;
                            System.out.println("Permitted subclasses of Shape:");
                            for (Class<?> subclass : shapeClass.getPermittedSubclasses()) {
                                System.out.println(" - " + subclass.getSimpleName());
                            }
                        }
                    }
    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Access Modifiers:

        -> Sealed classes can have any access modifier (public, protected, package-private, private).

        -> However, the permitted subclasses must be accessible to the sealed class at compile time.

        -> So, permited subclass modifier must be compatible with the sealed class's access level like public.
                    -> For example, 
                        sealed class Modifier          Permitted Subclass Modifier
                        ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                        public sealed class Shape           public final class Circle extends Shape
                        public sealed class Shape           final class Circle extends Shape
                        public sealed class Shape           sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        public sealed class Shape           non-sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                        private sealed class Shape          private final class Circle extends Shape
                        private sealed class Shape          final class Circle extends Shape
                        private sealed class Shape          sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        private sealed class Shape          non-sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                        package-private sealed class Shape  package-private final class Circle extends Shape
                        package-private sealed class Shape  final class Circle extends Shape
                        package-private sealed class Shape  sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        package-private sealed class Shape  non-sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                        protected sealed class Shape        protected final class Circle extends Shape
                        protected sealed class Shape        final class Circle extends Shape       
                        protected sealed class Shape        sealed class Circle extends Shape
                        protected sealed class Shape        non-sealed class Circle extends Shape  
                        ------------------------------------------------------------------------
            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    final class Circle extends Shape { }

                    final class Square extends Shape { }

                    final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Record Classes:

        -> Record classes can also be used as permitted subclasses of a sealed class or interface.

        -> This allows for concise and immutable data carriers within a sealed hierarchy.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed interface Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape { }

                    public record Square(double side) implements Shape { }

                    public record Rectangle(double width, double height) implements Shape { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Enums:

        -> Enums cannot be sealed classes, but they can implement a sealed interface.

        -> This allows for a fixed set of enum constants while still benefiting from the control provided by sealed interfaces.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed interface Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public enum BasicShape implements Shape {
                        CIRCLE, SQUARE, RECTANGLE
                    }
    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Generics:

        -> Sealed classes can also be generic, allowing for more flexible and reusable code while still controlling the inheritance hierarchy.

            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Box<T>
                        permits SmallBox, MediumBox, LargeBox { }

                    public final class SmallBox<T> extends Box<T> { }

                    public final class MediumBox<T> extends Box<T> { }

                    public final class LargeBox<T> extends Box<T> { }

    ---------------------------------------------------
    -> Sealed Classes and Modules:

        -> Sealed classes can be used in conjunction with Java's module system to further control access and visibility.
            
            -> Sealed class already restricts:
                -> Who can extend it (only permitted subclasses)
                -> Where it can be extended (same module or package)
            
            -> Java's module system allows you to control:
                -> Which packages are accessible to other modules
                -> Which classes are accessible within a module
                -> Before Java 9, all packages were mostly open to everyone.
                -> After Java 9, Java introduced MODULES, which allow you to define boundaries and control access between different parts of your application.
                    -> Example: 
                        -> Before Java 9:
                            -> All classes in all packages were accessible to everyone, which could lead to unintended usage and security issues.
                        -> After Java 9:
                            -> You can define a module and specify which packages are exported and which are not, providing better encapsulation and control over your codebase.

                        -> Code Example:

                                // In module-info.java
                                module com.example.shapes {
                                    exports com.example.shapes;
                                }

                                // In Shape.java
                                package com.example.shapes;

                                public sealed class Shape
                                    permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                                public final class Circle extends Shape { }

                                public final class Square extends Shape { }

                                public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }
                            
                            -> Above we created a module "com.example.shapes" and exported the package "com.example.shapes". 
                            -> The sealed class "Shape" and its permitted subclasses are all in the same package, which allows for better encapsulation and control over the hierarchy.

                        -> wrong code example:

                                // In module-info.java
                                module com.example.shapes {
                                    exports com.example.shapes;
                                }

                                // In Shape.java
                                package com.example.shapes;

                                public sealed class Shape
                                    permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                                public final class Circle extends Shape { }

                                public final class Square extends Shape { }

                                public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

                                // In another package
                                package com.example.other;

                                public final class Triangle extends Shape { } // Compile-time error: Triangle is not a permitted subclass of Shape

                            -> Above we have a class "Triangle" in a different package trying to extend "Shape", which will result in a compile-time error because "Triangle" is not a permitted subclass of "Shape" and is also in a different package.
                        
                        -> Now to allow there are two ways to fix this issue:
                            -> Different packages with same module: Using "permits" clause to declare Triangle as a permitted subclass of Shape even though it's in a different package
                               -> code example:

                                        // In module-info.java
                                        module com.example.shapes {
                                            exports com.example.shapes;
                                        }

                                        // In Shape.java
                                        package com.example.shapes;

                                        public sealed class Shape
                                            permits Circle, Square, Rectangle, Triangle { }

                                        public final class Circle extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Square extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Triangle extends Shape { }
                            
                            -> Moving Triangle class to the same package as Shape and declaring it as a permitted subclass
                               -> code example:
                                        // In module-info.java
                                        module com.example.shapes {
                                            exports com.example.shapes;
                                        }

                                        // In Shape.java
                                        package com.example.shapes;

                                        public sealed class Shape
                                            permits Circle, Square, Rectangle, Triangle { }

                                        public final class Circle extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Square extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

                                        public final class Triangle extends Shape { }


        -> Permitted subclasses must be in the same module or package as the sealed class, which allows for better encapsulation and modular design.
