    -> Narrowing Reference Conversion and Disjoint Types
        -> Casting meaning:
            -> Converting a reference of one type to another type
            -> Example: 
                Object obj = "Hello";
                String str = (String) obj; // Casting Object to String
            -> Two important things in casting:
                -> Compile time check: Compiler checks if the cast is valid based on the class hierarchy
                    -> Example:
                        Object obj = "Hello";
                        Integer num = (Integer) obj; // Compile-time error: Cannot cast Object to Integer
                -> Runtime check: JVM checks if the actual object can be cast to the target type at runtime
                    -> Example:
                        Object obj = "Hello";
                        String str = (String) obj; // Valid cast, works at runtime
                        Integer num = (Integer) obj; // Runtime error: ClassCastException
                -> Interesting case when compile time check passes but runtime check fails:
                    -> Example:
                        Object obj = "Hello";
                        String str = (String) obj; // Valid cast, works at runtime
                        Object anotherObj = new Object();
                        String anotherStr = (String) anotherObj; // Runtime error: ClassCastException
                        Reason: At compile time, the cast is valid because Object can be cast to String, 
                                but at runtime, the actual object is not a String, leading to a ClassCastException.
                        
                        Mesh of two object references:
                            -> At compile time, the compiler sees that both references are of type Object, so it allows the cast to String.
                            -> At runtime, the JVM checks the actual object that "anotherObj" refers to, which is not a String, resulting in a ClassCastException.
        -> Disjoint types:
            -> Two types are disjoint if they do not share any common subtype
            -> Example:
                class A { }
                class B { }
                A and B are disjoint types because there is no common subtype that can be cast to both A and B.
            -> In the context of sealed classes, if you have two sealed classes that do not share any common permitted subclasses, they are considered disjoint types.
                -> Example:
                    public sealed class Shape
                        permits Circle, Square { }

                    public sealed class Color
                        permits Red, Green { }

                    Shape and Color are disjoint types because they do not share any common permitted subclasses. 
                    You cannot cast a Shape to a Color or vice versa, as they are unrelated in the type hierarchy.

        -> Narrowing reference conversion:
            -> A narrowing reference conversion is a type of cast that converts a reference of a supertype to a reference of a subtype.
            -> Example:
                Object obj = "Hello";
                String str = (String) obj; // Narrowing reference conversion from Object to String
            -> In the context of sealed classes, if you have a reference of a sealed class type, you can perform a narrowing reference conversion to one of its permitted subclasses.
                -> Example:
                    Shape shape = new Circle(5.0);
                    Circle circle = (Circle) shape; // Narrowing reference conversion from Shape to Circle
                    This is valid because Circle is a permitted subclass of Shape, and the actual object referred to by "shape" is indeed an instance of Circle.

        -> Now narrowing reference conversion with disjoint types:
            -> If you have two disjoint types, you cannot perform a narrowing reference conversion between them because there is no common subtype that can be cast to both types.
            -> Example:
                Shape shape = new Circle(5.0);
                Color color = (Color) shape; // Compile-time error: Cannot cast Shape to Color
                This is invalid because Shape and Color are disjoint types, and there is no common subtype that can be cast to both Shape and Color.
    
