    -> APIs Related to Sealed Classes and Interfaces
        -> The class java.lang.Class has two important methods related to sealed classes:
            -> isSealed(): Returns true if the class is a sealed class or interface, false otherwise.
            -> getPermittedSubclasses(): Returns an array of Class objects representing the permitted subclasses of the sealed class or interface. 
                If the class is not a sealed class or interface, it returns an empty array.
            -> Example:

                    public sealed class Shape
                        permits Circle, Square, Rectangle { }

                    public final class Circle extends Shape { }

                    public final class Square extends Shape { }

                    public final class Rectangle extends Shape { }

                    public class SealedClassAPIExample {
                        public static void main(String[] args) {
                            Class<?> shapeClass = Shape.class;
                            System.out.println("Is Shape a sealed class? " + shapeClass.isSealed());
                            System.out.println("Permitted subclasses of Shape:");
                            for (Class<?> subclass : shapeClass.getPermittedSubclasses()) {
                                System.out.println(" - " + subclass.getSimpleName());
                            }
                    output:
                            Is Shape a sealed class? true
                            Permitted subclasses of Shape:
                             - Circle
                             - Square
                             - Rectangle
                        }
                    }
    ---------------------------------------------------

    -> Important Notes:

        -> Sealed class must be declared with "sealed" keyword

        -> Permitted subclasses must be listed in "permits" clause

        -> Permitted subclasses must be in the same module or package

        -> Permitted subclasses must be final, sealed, or non-sealed

        -> Sealed classes cannot be abstract

        -> Sealed classes can be interfaces or records

        -> Sealed classes work well with pattern matching and switch expressions

    